english:
  title: A Preface to Poems Sent Off with Envoy Luo on His Return
  author: Jung Jong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In ancient times, the office of envoy held mastery over the protocols of hospitality, drawing near the feudal lords and attending to the four corners of the realm—such was the noble practice by which the sages of old secured the great peace. The Imperial Ming, having received the Mandate of Heaven, established its institutions with care. All rites were refined through reform and revision, with each decision flowing from the imperial mind itself, harmonizing with antiquity while serving the present age. The Bureau of Envoys and its officers exemplify this principle perfectly. Those chosen for such a post must possess bearing noble enough to honor the nation's commission and eloquence sufficient to proclaim the nation's virtue. Who else could be entrusted with such a charge?

    In the autumn of the eighteenth year of Hongwu, the Son of Heaven extended his grace to our Goryeo, issuing an imperial edict to bestow the posthumous name Gongmin upon the late king, and to invest the heir apparent with the rank of king. Seeking a man of both refined bearing and dignified speech—one who could convey this mandate with proper ceremony and fully express the imperial favor—the Emperor himself selected two worthies from among the realm's finest scholars: Zhou Gong, keeper of records at the National Academy, and Envoy Luo. Presenting them with the seal and scepter of office, he dispatched them from the imperial court, their radiance and honor to shine upon the distant realm. Truly, a glorious undertaking!

    When Envoy Luo arrived, he proclaimed the imperial edict with utmost ceremony. His mission fulfilled, he prepared to return. All the literate men of our nation composed verses in his honor, gathering them into a single scroll. They entrusted this collection to me, Jung Jong, asking that I compose a preface.

    I humbly bow and present these words: The sage emperor, remembering the late king's sincere submission, has graciously bestowed exceptional titles and honors upon his successor, instructing him to serve his sovereign with loyalty and his ancestors with filial devotion, confirming him in his inherited rank. Thus the Emperor's intention to cherish the feudal lords stands complete. Envoy Luo possesses refined deportment and cultivated speech, well versed in the affairs of the age. His bearing and eloquence truly honor the nation's commission and proclaim the nation's excellence—he embodies the very purpose for which the Emperor established the office of envoy and receives the four quarters. Yet Envoy Luo must not delay his departure. Let these verses be gathered and presented to the imperial historian, that our distant, humble realm may be seen as residing within the transformative influence of the sage. This grace flows from Envoy Luo's mission. All agreed to this, and so I record these words as the preface to poems sent off with Envoy Luo.
  footnotes:
    - 'Hongwu: The founding era of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1398), suggesting this poem commemorates a diplomatic moment early in Ming-Goryeo relations.'
    - The 'seal and scepter of office' (冊與節) were symbols of imperial authority granted to envoys, legitimizing their diplomatic mission.
    - Jung Jong positions this preface as a response to imperial grace, turning a diplomatic moment into a literary commemoration of the relationship between the two realms.
